---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import Link from '../../components/Link.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/TableOfContents.astro';
const title = 'Prop Asset Creation - Cities Skylines Modding';
import ResponsiveImage from '../../components/ResponsiveImage.astro';
import { images } from '../../data/imageImports.js';
---

<MainLayout title={title}>
	<TableOfContents />
	<section class="py-12 sm:ml-64 xl:mr-64 text-lg text-hit-gray-500">
		<div class="content">
			<h1 id="overview" class="border-b-4 border-hit-gray-600 pb-8 text-4xl font-bold text-hit-gray-400">Prop Asset Creation</h1>
			<h2 class="border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 mt-24 pb-8 text-4xl font-medium text-hit-gray-400" id="mesh">Mesh</h2>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="main-mesh">Main Mesh</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				This is a 3D model of the prop, which will be visible when the camera is close to it. The actual mesh file contains vertices (their coordinates, UV
				mapping, normals, and colors) and triangles.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">It's created using 3D modeling software such as Blender, 3ds Max, Maya or SketchUp.</p>
			<h4 class="text-xl text-hit-gray-400 font-medium border-b border-hit-gray-950 pb-4 mt-8 lg:mt-12" id="model-complexity">Model Complexity</h4>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						It's recommended to stay within reasonable triangle counts based on the size and detail of your model. You may look at examples of vanilla props or
						assets by other creators for reference.
					</p><p class="mt-4">The absolute limit for a mesh is 65536 vertices.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/prop/prtris.jpg" target="_blank">
						<ResponsiveImage
							src={images.prtris}
							naturalHeight={874}
							naturalWidth={2232}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 1000, 1400, 1600, 1800, 2000]}
							alt="Triangle counts of some vanilla props"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Triangle counts of some vanilla props.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-hoverlink flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path d="M12 9v3.75m9-.75a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0zm-9 3.75h.008v.008H12v-.008z" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						You can use <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=453956891"
							text="Mesh Info by SamsamTS"
							theme="externallink"
						/> to check triangle counts of assets.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="lod-mesh">LOD Mesh</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						LOD stands for level of detail. This is the mesh visible from a distance. It must be as simple as possible. Props are usually very small so a model
						with 1-6 triangles could be enough.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						If you don't provide an LOD mesh, the game will try to generate one automatically, which may have visual issues, so it's highly recommended to make
						a custom LOD mesh.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/prop/prlodmesh.jpg" target="_blank">
						<ResponsiveImage
							src={images.prlodmesh}
							naturalHeight={437}
							naturalWidth={1488}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 1000, 1200, 1400]}
							alt="Comparison between main and LOD meshes for the vanilla grill kiosk"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Comparison between main and LOD meshes for the vanilla grill kiosk.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="uv-mapping">UV Mapping</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						For the main mesh, you are allowed to UV map outside the 0-1 area (main tile), so you can tile the entire texture multiple times on a single face.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/uv_main.jpg" target="_blank"
						><ResponsiveImage
							src={images.uv_main}
							naturalHeight={437}
							naturalWidth={560}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 500]}
							alt="Example UV mapping using visible horizontal tiling on the bottom"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example UV mapping using visible horizontal tiling on the bottom.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h4 class="text-xl text-hit-gray-400 font-medium border-b border-hit-gray-950 pb-4 mt-8 lg:mt-12" id="uv-mapping-lod">LOD</h4>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						For the LOD mesh, the UV mapping must be within the 0-1 area (main tile) of the UV map, no tiling is allowed. This is because ingame all the LOD
						textures are combined into a single texture called an atlas, so having incorrect uv mapping will end up putting the texture of some other random
						prop on your LOD.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/uv_lod.jpg" target="_blank"
						><ResponsiveImage
							src={images.uv_lod}
							naturalHeight={475}
							naturalWidth={605}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 500, 600]}
							alt="UV mapping for LOD mesh using automatic mapping in 3ds Max"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">
						UV mapping for LOD mesh using automatic mapping in 3ds Max. No overlap and contained within the main tile - good for baking.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="pivot-origin">Pivot / Origin</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The pivot point or origin represents the center point on the ground, where the prop will be plopped. It's usually represented using a red/green/blue
				axis gizmo.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="transform">Transform</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Make sure you are exporting a single object, which doesn't have any rotation or scale.<br />This can be done using <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://wiki.blender.org/index.php/User:Fade/Doc:2.6/Manual/3D_interaction/Transform_Control/Reset_Object_Transformations#Apply_Object_transformations"
					text='"apply rotation & scale" in Blender'
					theme="externallink"
				/>, or <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://knowledge.autodesk.com/support/3ds-max/learn-explore/caas/CloudHelp/cloudhelp/2017/ENU/3DSMax/files/GUID-B98414B9-4F28-45F4-A1F4-9DA994548ED9-htm.html"
					text='"reset xform" in 3ds Max'
					theme="externallink"
				/>, and exporting only the selected object.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="vertex-paint">Vertex Paint</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>The vertex color blue channel determines snow behavior on winter maps - 0 means no snow will be visible.</p><p class="mt-4">
						Vertex colors are also used for specific shaders like <Link classes="" href="/shader/animuv/" text="AnimUV" theme="internallink" /> for scrolling or
						multi-frame animations, or <Link classes="" href="/mod/proprotating-params/" text="PropRotating" theme="internallink" /> for rotating animations.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/vertexpaint.jpg" target="_blank"
						><ResponsiveImage
							src={images.vertexpaint}
							naturalHeight={442}
							naturalWidth={930}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 900]}
							alt="Vertex painting in 3ds Max"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Vertex painting in 3ds Max.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="culling">Culling</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>Prop culling is when a prop disappears when you look away from the center of it.</p><p class="mt-4">
						If your prop has a low height or is wide/long, it's recommended to add an invisible triangle which is bigger than your actual mesh to make the game
						think the prop is larger than it actually is, which will reduce the chance of it disappearing.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/prop/prculling.jpg" target="_blank"
						><ResponsiveImage
							src={images.prculling}
							naturalHeight={886}
							naturalWidth={1500}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 900, 1200, 1500]}
							alt="Infinitely thin triangles made by putting 2 of the 3 vertices in the same place"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Infinitely thin triangles made by putting 2 of the 3 vertices in the same place.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="formats">Formats</h3>
			<ul class="mt-4 list-disc list-inside">
				<li class="mt-4">FBX (2015 or older) (most commonly used)</li>
				<li class="mt-4">OBJ (doesn't support vertex colors)</li>
				<li class="mt-4">DAE</li>
			</ul>
			<h2 class="border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 mt-24 pb-8 text-4xl font-medium text-hit-gray-400" id="textures">Textures</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">These determine the color and material properties of your prop.</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="resolution">Resolution</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>All imported main textures must be the same resolution.</p><p class="mt-4">
						Powers of 2 is a standard practice in 3D graphics, which means resolutions such as 1024x1024, 1024x512, 256x512, 2048x128 etc. It is recommended to
						stick to this standard, otherwise, your texture may be corrupted by compression, which may be more visible at longer distances or grazing angles.
						The smallest allowed resolution is 32x32.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/prop/prtextsize.jpg" target="_blank"
						><ResponsiveImage
							src={images.prtextsize}
							naturalHeight={1000}
							naturalWidth={1608}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 900, 1200, 1500, 1600]}
							alt="Texture sizes of various vanilla assets"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Texture sizes of various vanilla assets. See the resolution in the top right corner of the preview window.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-orange flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m-9.303 3.376c-.866 1.5.217 3.374 1.948 3.374h14.71c1.73 0 2.813-1.874 1.948-3.374L13.949 3.378c-.866-1.5-3.032-1.5-3.898 0L2.697 16.126zM12 15.75h.007v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						Make sure texture quality is set to high in the game's graphics settings, otherwise, your imported textures will be downscaled to a lower
						resolution.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="lod-textures">LOD Textures</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">All imported LOD textures must be the same resolution.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				If you don't provide LOD textures, the game will try to bake them using the UV mapping your LOD mesh has, and that may cause visual issues, so it's
				recommended that you create your own LOD textures using baking.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="diffuse">Diffuse</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>The main color and texture of your asset.</p><p class="mt-4">
						It will look very bright, contrasty, and saturated in the game, so make sure to reduce the saturation and limit the brightest parts to a
						medium/light gray below 140 RGB.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a diffuse map, it will default to white.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/prop/prdiff.jpg" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.prdiff}
								naturalHeight={512}
								naturalWidth={512}
								srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 900, 1200, 1500]}
								alt="Example diffuse texture for a conveyor prop"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example diffuse texture for a conveyor prop.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/color_guidelines.png" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.color_guidelines}
								naturalHeight={1024}
								naturalWidth={1024}
								srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 1000]}
								alt="Color guidelines"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Color guidelines.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="alpha">Alpha</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Transparency, white means opaque or visible, black means transparent or invisible. Gray values may affect how it looks from a distance or at an
						angle.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						Semi-transparency is not supported, you need to use the <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ELoMC1rWOSc"
							text="rotors shader"
							theme="externallink"
						/> for that.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import an alpha map, it will default to fully opaque or fully visible.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_alpha.jpg" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.textures_alpha}
								naturalHeight={220}
								naturalWidth={306}
								srcWidths={[200, 300]}
								alt="Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_alpha_rail.jpg" target="_blank">
							<ResponsiveImage
								src={images.textures_alpha_rail}
								naturalHeight={128}
								naturalWidth={256}
								srcWidths={[200, 250]}
								alt="Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Using lighter values for the invisible parts will decrease the chance of small details like railings disappearing completely.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="color">Color</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">Determines which parts will be affected by color variations. White means fully affected and black means not at all.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">The diffuse will get multiplied by the color variation, that means the resulting color will look darker than the original diffuse.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				If you don't import a color map, it will default to full color, but the "use color variations" setting must be enabled for the colors to appear.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="illumination">Illumination</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>Allows for diffuse contribution illumination. Black means no illumination and white means the brightest possible illumination.</p><p class="mt-4">
						<Link
							classes=""
							href="/asset/prop/#m_illuminationblinktype"
							text="There are parameters for blinking illumination or disabling illumination during the day."
							theme="internallink"
						/>
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import an illumination map, it will default to no illumination.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/prop/prillum.jpg" target="_blank">
						<ResponsiveImage
							src={images.prillum}
							naturalHeight={256}
							naturalWidth={64}
							srcWidths={[64]}
							alt="Example illumination map for a torch"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="max-h-40 max-w-full"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example illumination map for a torch.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="specular">Specular</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>Reflectivity, black means no reflection and white means max reflection.</p><p class="mt-4">
						The specular highlight from the sun is very big and bright, so you might want to use very low (0-10%) specularity for surfaces facing upwards.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a specular map, it will default to no specularity.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/prop/prspec.jpg" target="_blank">
							<ResponsiveImage
								src={images.prspec}
								naturalHeight={512}
								naturalWidth={512}
								srcWidths={[300, 400, 500]}
								alt="Example specular map for a roof water tank"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example specular map for a roof water tank.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_specular_transition.jpg" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.textures_specular_transition}
								naturalHeight={293}
								naturalWidth={511}
								srcWidths={[300, 400, 500]}
								alt="Transitions between different specular values produce artifacts on the normal map and vice versa"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Transitions between different specular values produce artifacts on the normal map and vice versa, even if a normal map is not imported.
						</p>
					</div>
